2. volume drivers
While running a docker container, volume can be created with volume plugins like local, EBS, Azure file storage.

3. Container storage interface
Docker container use CSI (container storage interface) to store the data into third party storage tools like Amazon EBS, Azure file storage


Note: when a pod is created and trying to get the volume from local, EBS......
CSI will help to schedule a new volume for the pod from Amazon EBS

A. Provision a new volume on the pod
B. Provision a new volume on the storage
C. delete a volume on the pod
D. volume on a pod


4. Persistent Volume:
PV is cretead by a admin and mapped to the storage like GCP, AMAZON EBC, AZURE FILE
It can define the storage limit from the storage resource and accessmode like read, write in it.

5. Persistent Volume Claim:
PVC is created by a developer and he don't know how much volume is required for the logs where the application written on it.
It will define the storage request by developer from persistent volume. Also accesmode like read, write.

Note:
Pod will define the container and mount volume in it.
In the volume define pvc.
Pvc will get pv.
PV will attach with the storage resources like EBS.



6. Storage Class:
Storage class is use to get the storage from the EBS like dynamic way. No need to mention the limit of the storage request.

POD --> PVC ---> Storage Class

Storage class will automatically create a PV. 

In the stoageclass.yml need to mention the classes of storage like silver, gold, platinum.





